<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="34.[667,1194,213,1152]" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">
COMMENTS: In the original description, Stresemann gave Raap’s number of the 
<typeStatus box="[667,769,420,442]" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">holotype</typeStatus>
but not the sex, noted that it was in the Rothschild Collection, and gave measurements for five specimens of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">leptorhynchus</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[833,935,509,531]" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">holotype</typeStatus>
is the only specimen that includes Raap’s original label with his no. 34 and is sexed as a female. Apparently, both Stresemann and Hartert doubted the sexing; 
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3059913560" collectionCode="AMNH" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" specimenCode="AMNH 667595-667598" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="paratype">
<bibRefCitation author="Hartert" box="[753,973,626,648]" firstAuthor="Hartert" page="135" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" pagination="123 - 178" refId="ref125804" refString="Hartert, E. 1919. Types of birds in the Tring Museum. B. Types in the general collection. Novitates Zoologicae 26: 123 - 178." type="journal article" year="1919">Hartert (1919: 135)</bibRefCitation>
included the sex in quotation marks. The four 
<typeStatus box="[1020,1133,657,678]" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">paratypes</typeStatus>
are: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[667,944,686,707]" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">
<specimenCode box="[667,944,686,707]" collectionCode="AMNH" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34925" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34925" name="American Museum of Natural History" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">AMNH 667595–667598</specimenCode>
</emphasis>
, all collected on Pini by Raap
</materialsCitation>
; none are dated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[667,1194,213,1152]" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">
<bibRefCitation author="Van Steenis-Kruseman" box="[696,1124,745,768]" firstAuthor="Van Steenis-Kruseman" page="421" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 639" refId="ref139210" refString="van Steenis-Kruseman, M. J. 1950. Malaysian plant collectors and collections being a cyclopaedia of botanical exploration in Malaysia and a guide to the concerned literature up to the year 1950. Flora Malesiana 1 (1): 1 - 639, photographs." type="journal article" year="1950">Van Steenis-Kruseman (1950: 421)</bibRefCitation>
gave details of Raap’s plant collecting in the Batu Islands; he was on P. Pini 
<date pageId="34" pageNumber="34" value="1896-10-28" valueMax="1896-11-14" valueMin="1896-10-28">28 October–14 November 1896</date>
and 
<date box="[945,1189,834,856]" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" value="1897-01-04" valueMax="1897-01-14" valueMin="1897-01-04">4–14 January 1897</date>
. Presumably he was collecting birds at the same time.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[667,1194,213,1152]" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">
<bibRefCitation author="Meyer de Schauensee" box="[696,1125,923,946]" firstAuthor="Meyer de Schauensee" page="41 - 42" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" pagination="23 - 42" refId="ref131575" refString="Meyer de Schauensee, R. 1940. The birds of the Batu Islands. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 92: 23 - 42, map." type="journal article" year="1940">Meyer de Schauensee (1940: 41–42)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ripley" firstAuthor="Ripley" page="405 - 406" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" pagination="307 - 430" refId="ref133593" refString="Ripley, S. D. 1944. The bird fauna of the west Sumatra islands. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology 94: 307 - 430, 2 pls." type="book chapter" year="1944">Ripley (1944: 405–406)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="van Marle and Voous" firstAuthor="van Marle" page="195 - 196" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" refId="ref138792" refString="van Marle, J. G., and K. H. Voous. 1988. The birds of Sumatra. British Ornithologists' Union Checklist 10. Tring: British Ornithologists' Union, 265 pp." type="book" year="1988">van Marle and Voous (1988: 195–196)</bibRefCitation>
synonymized 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">leptorhyncha</emphasis>
with 
<emphasis box="[822,974,1011,1034]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="34">pachistorhina</emphasis>
based on overlap in wing measurements, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Amadon" firstAuthor="Amadon" page="18" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref118901" refString="Amadon, D. 1956. Remarks on the starlings, family Sturnidae. American Museum Novitates 1803: 1 - 41, 3 figs." type="book chapter" year="1956">Amadon (1956: 18)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Craig and Feare" box="[769,1109,1071,1093]" firstAuthor="Craig" page="720" pageId="34" pageNumber="34" pagination="711 - 758" refId="ref121775" refString="Craig, A. J. F. K., and C. J. Feare. 2009. Family Sturnidae (starlings), species accounts. In J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott and D. A. Christie (editors). Handbook of the birds of the world. Vol. 14, Bush-shrikes to Old World sparrows: 711 - 758. Barcelona: Lynx Edicions, 893 pp, 51 pls., photographs." type="book chapter" year="2009">Craig and Feare (2009: 720)</bibRefCitation>
recognized it, noting its very slender bill and pure blue gloss on the plumage.
</paragraph>
